# Exercise 1: Implementing the Singleton Pattern

## Objective
To understand and implement the Singleton Design Pattern in Java.

## Description
The Singleton Pattern is a creational design pattern that ensures only one instance of a class is created throughout the application and provides a global access point to that instance.

## Files Included

- `Singleton.java` - Contains the Singleton class implementation.
- `SingletonTest.java` - Contains the test code to verify the Singleton behavior.

## Implementation Details

### Singleton Class
- Constructor is declared as `private` to prevent direct object creation.
- A static instance variable is used to store the single object.
- A public static method `getInstance()` returns the same object every time it is called.

### Test Class
- Creates two references using `Singleton.getInstance()`.
- Verifies that both references point to the same object.

## Code Execution

### Compile

```bash
javac Exercise1/*.java
```

### Run

```bash
java Exercise1.SingletonTest
```

## Sample Output

```text
Exercise1.Singleton@7344699f
Exercise1.Singleton@7344699f
true
```

## Explanation of Output

- Both references display the same memory address.
- `true` confirms that both references point to the same object.
- This verifies that only one instance of the Singleton class exists.

## Learning Outcomes

- Understanding of the Singleton Design Pattern.
- Use of private constructors.
- Use of static variables and methods.
- Object reference comparison using `==`.
- Implementation of a common creational design pattern.

## Conclusion

The Singleton Pattern was successfully implemented and tested. The output confirms that only one instance of the class is created and shared throughout the application.